1
00:00:00,960 --> 00:00:01,770
Hi everyone!

2
00:00:02,450 --> 00:00:04,350
Happy Radio Day, everyone.

3
00:00:04,650 --> 00:00:11,370
One way or another, anyone who's ever soldered something can consider themselves part of this holiday.

4
00:00:12,930 --> 00:00:25,010
It sometimes happens that in everyday life or for experiments you need some little thing — ideally simple, that can be made quickly, that raises voltage.

5
00:00:25,010 --> 00:00:32,510
In particular, I needed a circuit like this for electronic ignition.

6
00:00:33,910 --> 00:00:39,710
The electronic ignition board itself switches via a coil like this.

7
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:47,310
But for successful switching I needed to apply 70 volts to the primary winding of this coil.

8
00:00:47,310 --> 00:00:56,530
And the on-board power is 12 volts, so I have to build a converter like this.

9
00:00:57,270 --> 00:01:14,990
But I decided right away that my converter will be not only at 70 volts — I marked a tap for that — but I'll also do the full 220 volts, so on the road I could charge a mobile

10
00:01:14,990 --> 00:01:20,330
phone or light up a 220-volt lamp.

11
00:01:20,770 --> 00:01:24,070
You can also charge laptops and other stuff.

12
00:01:24,430 --> 00:01:27,690
So, the task is set — now we just have to settle on the schematic.

13
00:01:27,690 --> 00:01:36,970
I stopped at this schematic solution, on the pretty common IR2153 chip.

14
00:01:38,050 --> 00:01:42,090
In the radio-amateur world it's been nicknamed "Irka" for a long time.

15
00:01:43,590 --> 00:01:49,490
The chip has proven itself well, but you have to be careful here.

16
00:01:49,590 --> 00:01:56,730
There are IR2153 chips, and there's the same abbreviation with a D suffix.

17
00:01:56,730 --> 00:02:02,010
For this converter we need specifically the IR2153.

18
00:02:02,890 --> 00:02:12,010
The chip with the D suffix has a diode in the package between pins 1 and 8.

19
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:17,990
These solutions, on the contrary, aren't designed for step-up converters but for step-down ones.

20
00:02:18,350 --> 00:02:26,450
On a half-bridge or bridge basis — if you use two control chips for a bridge.

21
00:02:27,870 --> 00:02:33,610
So at purchase, pay attention so there's no D suffix here.

22
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:52,140
If you have lab gear — power supplies, oscilloscope and other equipment — you'll find it quite easy to tune this circuit, and an experienced radio amateur handles it without

23
00:02:52,140 --> 00:02:52,520
problems.

24
00:02:52,520 --> 00:03:04,920
But if you decided to just build a converter for everyday needs and you have no equipment, that's actually not a problem.

25
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:07,480
I'll show you how to do it.

26
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:09,600
We'll follow a few rules.

27
00:03:11,320 --> 00:03:13,020
First basic rule.

28
00:03:14,040 --> 00:03:22,420
Assemble the control side with the transistors, without connecting the step-up transformer itself.

29
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:28,540
And start it up — check mounting, and startup is mandatory.

30
00:03:28,660 --> 00:03:36,680
Connect a 12 V lamp from 10 to 21 W in series in the power path.

31
00:03:37,800 --> 00:03:49,580
If on startup the lamp glows or lights up, immediately turn off and understand that an error was made somewhere in the circuit.

32
00:03:49,580 --> 00:03:59,480
If the lamp doesn't light, then you can connect the transformer next and check with it.

33
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:07,740
I recommend starting through a lamp because usually at home there's some power source.

34
00:04:07,980 --> 00:04:12,800
Usually it's the same battery that'll power the converter.

35
00:04:12,800 --> 00:04:19,880
If you don't put a lamp at the input, this thing might blow very fast.

36
00:04:20,020 --> 00:04:26,980
It'll be frustrating and discourage any further desire from a beginner to deal with electronics.

37
00:04:29,480 --> 00:04:37,940
To start checking the circuit without instruments, we need to solder a lamp in series with the power.

38
00:04:38,590 --> 00:04:46,700
And take two more lamps that'll serve as the load for these transistors.

39
00:04:46,800 --> 00:04:50,080
They'll be connected instead of these windings.

40
00:04:50,580 --> 00:04:53,740
Check our circuit for errors.

41
00:04:54,580 --> 00:05:02,600
Connect the minus terminal of the power to minus, plus through the lamp to plus.

42
00:05:03,360 --> 00:05:12,360
You can notice the circuit is discharging now — visible that a small spark slips through here.

43
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:16,500
See in practice — this is the electrolytics charging.

44
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:19,360
And the lamp doesn't light up.

45
00:05:19,620 --> 00:05:28,040
We can rotate the variable resistor, and as you can see, the lamp doesn't light in any mode.

46
00:05:28,040 --> 00:05:36,040
This confirms we already assembled the circuit correctly, and most likely it'll work.

47
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:39,880
Now we should check whether the switches work.

48
00:05:41,040 --> 00:05:44,020
Now we'll solder lamps and check.

49
00:05:45,180 --> 00:05:51,800
Lamps soldered — meaning lamps are now connected instead of these windings.

50
00:05:52,800 --> 00:05:56,820
The middle point the lamps connect to is this lead.

51
00:05:57,420 --> 00:06:01,820
It corresponds to this plus power wire.

52
00:06:01,940 --> 00:06:03,180
That is, this point.

53
00:06:04,900 --> 00:06:11,820
Before applying power, set the resistor slider roughly in the middle position.

54
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:17,660
That'll be about 30-40 kHz.

55
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:20,400
And apply power to the input.

56
00:06:21,620 --> 00:06:24,840
As you can see, the lamp doesn't light — nothing happens.

57
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:27,220
Checking the first transistor.

58
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:28,800
This is its lead.

59
00:06:29,020 --> 00:06:33,000
This is from its drain.

60
00:06:33,760 --> 00:06:36,300
These black wires are from the transistor drains.

61
00:06:36,480 --> 00:06:37,080
Checking.

62
00:06:37,640 --> 00:06:39,240
You see the lamp glows.

63
00:06:40,420 --> 00:06:44,500
The transistor works in operating mode.

64
00:06:44,580 --> 00:06:46,540
Now check the second transistor.

65
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:50,540
The lamp also glows.

66
00:06:51,380 --> 00:06:52,160
All normal.

67
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:56,700
With a dual-beam oscilloscope we can check the following.

68
00:06:56,780 --> 00:07:00,440
First we look at the signal at these points.

69
00:07:00,620 --> 00:07:03,480
On the FET gates.

70
00:07:04,340 --> 00:07:08,860
We need to confirm the circuit works correctly.

71
00:07:09,060 --> 00:07:13,320
And that there's so-called dead time between control signals.

72
00:07:13,660 --> 00:07:14,120
Dead time.

73
00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:18,080
That is, time when the controls don't overlap.

74
00:07:18,720 --> 00:07:20,160
Apply power to the input.

75
00:07:21,220 --> 00:07:24,120
Watching the controls.

76
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:27,100
You can play with frequency.

77
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:28,800
Watch.

78
00:07:29,560 --> 00:07:38,060
The limit is somewhere up to 100 kHz.

79
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:45,100
And the minimum is 12.8 kHz.

80
00:07:45,600 --> 00:07:51,440
We're interested in operation from 20 kHz.

81
00:07:52,480 --> 00:07:55,880
Let's stop at about 30 kHz.

82
00:07:56,660 --> 00:07:57,540
And look.

83
00:07:59,360 --> 00:08:00,780
The signal is rectangular.

84
00:08:00,880 --> 00:08:03,420
Now we check for the presence of dead time.

85
00:08:04,420 --> 00:08:07,980
Offset the signals from each other.

86
00:08:08,100 --> 00:08:17,360
And observe that there are actually pauses between the work of one arm and the other.

87
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:22,620
You can pay attention to the flat front.

88
00:08:23,420 --> 00:08:26,380
The transistor-opening front.

89
00:08:26,380 --> 00:08:34,180
This is the work of the built-in internal drivers through the resistor on the transistor gate.

90
00:08:35,280 --> 00:08:38,560
Next is gate capacitance discharge.

91
00:08:38,920 --> 00:08:40,500
It's steeper.

92
00:08:40,740 --> 00:08:43,920
Falls through the 1 kΩ resistor.

93
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:47,420
Normal signal.

94
00:08:50,120 --> 00:08:51,720
It'll work.

95
00:08:54,720 --> 00:09:00,090
Now we'll look at the switch operation under load.

96
00:09:00,720 --> 00:09:04,860
We'll look at the lamps at these points.

97
00:09:05,300 --> 00:09:07,600
On the transistor drains.

98
00:09:11,260 --> 00:09:14,840
I connected the probes at these points.

99
00:09:15,600 --> 00:09:17,200
You can see they're on the lamps.

100
00:09:17,320 --> 00:09:20,100
The measurement is done relative to the common wire.

101
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:24,000
The oscilloscope common is on the minus of the power source.

102
00:09:25,280 --> 00:09:26,860
Apply power.

103
00:09:29,780 --> 00:09:32,400
You see — the load works.

104
00:09:32,820 --> 00:09:35,740
And what does this oscillogram tell us?

105
00:09:37,920 --> 00:09:46,280
If we look at the oscillogram on the lamps, we see that operation happens with overlap.

106
00:09:47,280 --> 00:09:56,100
This is a normal oscillogram because don't forget that the FET inverts on voltage.

107
00:09:56,980 --> 00:10:05,140
So the switch operation will be in this zone when voltage drops to zero.

108
00:10:05,140 --> 00:10:09,120
Now I'll come back.

109
00:10:09,640 --> 00:10:13,700
The switch opens, voltage drops.

110
00:10:14,660 --> 00:10:16,960
The switch operates and closes.

111
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:26,060
We can see — here's the first switch working, a pause, and here the second switch.

112
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:33,680
On this load we've verified the circuit works correctly.

113
00:10:33,680 --> 00:10:41,400
You can sweep through the frequency range and check that dead time is preserved.

114
00:10:42,640 --> 00:10:44,020
This suits us.

115
00:10:44,220 --> 00:10:45,480
Next step.

116
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:49,420
Circuit checked — it's working, runs correctly.

117
00:10:50,880 --> 00:10:53,780
And move on to the step-up transformer.

118
00:10:54,300 --> 00:11:02,640
Say I took ferrite, a ring, and wound the secondary winding on it.

119
00:11:04,300 --> 00:11:07,840
The step-up turn count is picked individually.

120
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:13,640
There are programs you can use to calculate it, but at home we won't bother with that.

121
00:11:13,780 --> 00:11:20,320
We wound the winding, connected it, checked the voltage at the output with a multimeter.

122
00:11:20,820 --> 00:11:22,560
If we're happy, leave it.

123
00:11:22,620 --> 00:11:25,280
If not, then add more turns until you reach the target.

124
00:11:25,800 --> 00:11:27,960
And wind the primary winding.

125
00:11:27,960 --> 00:11:32,600
The primary winding is wound all in one direction.

126
00:11:33,260 --> 00:11:36,180
The same turn count per arm.

127
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:40,380
With a tap from the middle.

128
00:11:40,900 --> 00:11:54,080
Don't forget that the whole winding goes in one direction — because from inexperience you might wind in different directions, and then the converter will blow up.

129
00:11:54,080 --> 00:12:00,540
I assembled the circuit, connected a 15 W load at 220 V.

130
00:12:01,360 --> 00:12:04,620
And here I should explain one important point.

131
00:12:05,140 --> 00:12:16,980
Even after you've verified the circuit works, don't disconnect this lamp during the first startups with the step-up transformer.

132
00:12:16,980 --> 00:12:27,780
Because switch operation on lamps — on active resistance — is completely different from when the switch works on a reactive load.

133
00:12:28,380 --> 00:12:29,960
That is, on a coil.

134
00:12:31,840 --> 00:12:33,520
Let me show you visually.

135
00:12:34,220 --> 00:12:35,120
Apply power.

136
00:12:37,240 --> 00:12:38,660
As we thought.

137
00:12:39,020 --> 00:12:43,920
We don't need a big core for the power.

138
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:45,200
Our loads are small.

139
00:12:45,280 --> 00:12:48,560
Phone charging, some low-power lamp.

140
00:12:49,160 --> 00:12:50,940
At 20 W.

141
00:12:51,700 --> 00:12:53,420
Apply power.

142
00:12:53,520 --> 00:12:55,780
Here you see — the lamp lit.

143
00:12:56,360 --> 00:12:56,800
At the input.

144
00:12:57,080 --> 00:12:59,940
But the load barely glows.

145
00:13:00,820 --> 00:13:02,100
What's going on?

146
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:06,420
You can make a major mistake here.

147
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:10,260
You need to look at the signs of what's happening.

148
00:13:10,260 --> 00:13:14,140
First, you need to touch the heat sink and the switches.

149
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:19,700
You'll see the heat sink is heating up strongly.

150
00:13:19,980 --> 00:13:22,640
Plus the core itself is heating up strongly.

151
00:13:23,360 --> 00:13:31,020
If there weren't a limiting lamp here, smoke would come from this core.

152
00:13:31,480 --> 00:13:33,620
And the switches might have blown.

153
00:13:33,620 --> 00:13:40,220
Because in this situation, this core has entered saturation.

154
00:13:40,820 --> 00:13:47,240
Saturation is an unpleasant operating mode for the ferrite core.

155
00:13:47,740 --> 00:13:51,000
Turning off because it's already heated up strongly.

156
00:13:51,780 --> 00:13:57,120
A mode in which the core loses the property of remagnetizing.

157
00:13:57,120 --> 00:14:06,780
Since our circuit doesn't allow regulation of the control pulse duration.

158
00:14:07,040 --> 00:14:11,420
Which is actually the duration of switch opening when working on the load.

159
00:14:11,780 --> 00:14:19,080
Then we can't pick optimal parameters for this core by adjusting duration.

160
00:14:19,660 --> 00:14:25,780
Even increasing turn count or changing operating frequency won't lead anywhere.

161
00:14:26,620 --> 00:14:32,080
There's one way out — change the core of the step-up transformer itself.

162
00:14:32,420 --> 00:14:35,100
Until the circuit starts correctly.

163
00:14:35,420 --> 00:14:41,500
For this circuit I picked ferrite, also of the 2000 brand like this, but you can see its dimensions.

164
00:14:41,580 --> 00:14:45,980
It's slightly larger by outer diameter, and larger inside.

165
00:14:46,320 --> 00:14:53,560
But the main thing to be guided by isn't the diameters but the core's cross-section.

166
00:14:53,560 --> 00:15:03,340
If this magnetic core has a cross-section of 9 by 9 mm, then this one has a cross-section of 10 by 13 mm.

167
00:15:03,820 --> 00:15:11,640
And only such ferrite is the minimum possible core for this circuit to work correctly.

168
00:15:12,640 --> 00:15:16,520
Also note one more important point.

169
00:15:17,560 --> 00:15:26,320
You can check whether your core is suitable for this circuit only with the secondary winding present.

170
00:15:27,220 --> 00:15:34,720
If you wind the primary winding on the core without the secondary, it'll work.

171
00:15:36,180 --> 00:15:40,120
And may create the impression that this core is suitable.

172
00:15:40,120 --> 00:15:44,700
But as soon as you wind the secondary on it, it'll also enter saturation.

173
00:15:45,560 --> 00:15:54,060
So you have to check exclusively with at least several tens of turns of the secondary winding on the core.

174
00:15:55,600 --> 00:16:01,560
So, I installed the step-up transformer with a magnetic core of larger cross-section.

175
00:16:02,860 --> 00:16:04,700
And now we'll test it.

176
00:16:04,700 --> 00:16:11,700
Pay attention to how this load will glow now.

177
00:16:12,720 --> 00:16:20,140
And pay attention to how the spiral of the limiting lamp will heat up.

178
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:30,580
If in that experiment we connected and the load barely glowed while the lamp lit immediately, then look in this case.

179
00:16:31,500 --> 00:16:39,940
You see — the lamp doesn't heat up immediately, and the load shines much brighter.

180
00:16:40,480 --> 00:16:43,060
This confirms the circuit has already started.

181
00:16:43,220 --> 00:16:48,020
And you can hear the step-up transformer working.

182
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:56,420
Since we need the system to work inaudibly, we move its frequency into the inaudible range.

183
00:16:57,420 --> 00:16:58,420
Here.

184
00:17:00,420 --> 00:17:03,380
And the system runs quietly.

185
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:10,740
Now consumption is 13 V, 0.9 A.

186
00:17:10,820 --> 00:17:19,320
And now we can already check how the system behaves with a direct connection.

187
00:17:20,720 --> 00:17:29,940
You see the lamp shines at full brightness and the system works.

188
00:17:32,300 --> 00:17:40,180
Now I'll show a small nuance that many aren't familiar with.

189
00:17:41,180 --> 00:17:46,740
Pay attention to this capacitor.

190
00:17:46,740 --> 00:17:49,760
1 µF at 50 V, ceramic.

191
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:56,400
Which is at pin 8, directly next to the chip itself.

192
00:17:57,680 --> 00:18:01,080
On the board it's here.

193
00:18:01,980 --> 00:18:03,240
Very close.

194
00:18:04,040 --> 00:18:12,660
Its presence is mandatory because ceramic capacitors release charge faster than electrolytics.

195
00:18:12,660 --> 00:18:21,500
This improves the gate-opening system — that is, it saturates the gate capacitance faster.

196
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:27,080
And the built-in drivers in the chip can open the switches more sharply.

197
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:33,460
Since the switch opens more sharply, its switching time is much shorter.

198
00:18:33,960 --> 00:18:40,540
So the heat released in the switch tends to a minimum.

199
00:18:41,760 --> 00:18:46,700
Now we can check the circuit on a more serious load.

200
00:18:46,760 --> 00:18:57,360
In this case I'll use a 60 W load since my lab supply delivers 5 A maximum.

201
00:18:58,700 --> 00:19:04,600
Now I'll show how to tune the output for the load with turn count.

202
00:19:05,180 --> 00:19:09,840
Put it at the input directly and look — the lamp's lit.

203
00:19:09,840 --> 00:19:16,040
Now consumption is 4 A at 13 V.

204
00:19:19,680 --> 00:19:29,700
In this mode on a small load, you should run the converter for about 20 minutes.

205
00:19:32,540 --> 00:19:37,320
To check the thermal mode of the switches.

206
00:19:38,170 --> 00:19:40,100
The switches shouldn't heat up strongly.

207
00:19:40,860 --> 00:19:46,520
With a heat sink like this, there practically shouldn't be any heating.

208
00:19:46,940 --> 00:19:53,460
Maybe a bit above room temperature at such a load.

209
00:19:54,060 --> 00:19:57,060
You need to test and observe the converter.

210
00:19:58,020 --> 00:20:06,740
After this time, if you've confirmed everything works, you can move to bigger loads.

211
00:20:08,120 --> 00:20:15,680
Now let's also measure the voltage on the load.

212
00:20:15,980 --> 00:20:18,540
For this we need a multimeter.

213
00:20:35,790 --> 00:20:42,390
So we see we now have 195 V on the load.

214
00:20:46,150 --> 00:20:54,170
There's a sag — meaning we have 5 turns per arm now.

215
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:59,790
If there's a sag, we need to reduce the turn count.

216
00:20:59,790 --> 00:21:05,890
We saw in the previous measurement that there was a sag on the supply voltage.

217
00:21:07,270 --> 00:21:12,370
So to raise the voltage on the lamp, we have two options.

218
00:21:12,450 --> 00:21:19,150
Either add turns to the secondary winding or reduce the primary turn count.

219
00:21:19,470 --> 00:21:25,350
With the primary winding you need to work carefully — remove one turn at a time.

220
00:21:25,350 --> 00:21:28,890
I had 5 turns, now I made 4.

221
00:21:29,330 --> 00:21:31,110
And observe — apply power.

222
00:21:33,950 --> 00:21:38,910
And we see 230 V on the lamp.

223
00:21:39,030 --> 00:21:40,970
I only removed one turn.

224
00:21:41,410 --> 00:21:51,850
Now consumption has gone up — our converter has reached the 60 W load power.

225
00:21:52,850 --> 00:21:55,430
Here's the build I ended up with.

226
00:21:56,570 --> 00:22:04,570
The step-up transformer is mounted with a screw to the heat sink through a cardboard gasket.

227
00:22:05,450 --> 00:22:08,770
I settled on 5.5 turns for the primary.

228
00:22:08,910 --> 00:22:12,070
Here it is — the white wire.

229
00:22:13,990 --> 00:22:19,410
Installed a regular diode bridge — 4 diodes and reservoir cap.

230
00:22:19,410 --> 00:22:27,030
Also a discharge resistor of 820 kΩ at 1 W.

231
00:22:29,050 --> 00:22:34,930
It's for safety, so these caps discharge after some time.

232
00:22:36,370 --> 00:22:39,770
The whole mount is done by hanging mount.

233
00:22:41,130 --> 00:22:46,650
You can see the track wiring — the simplest build without PCB etching.

234
00:22:50,350 --> 00:22:54,310
Now we'll tune the circuit first.

235
00:22:55,150 --> 00:22:58,750
Pick the optimal mode with a trim pot.

236
00:22:58,970 --> 00:23:00,230
I'll show how this is done.

237
00:23:00,830 --> 00:23:05,490
And then move to full testing under load.

238
00:23:07,450 --> 00:23:15,690
To tune the system by frequency that optimally corresponds to this core, we need a load.

239
00:23:16,330 --> 00:23:19,430
A 40-volt lamp.

240
00:23:19,930 --> 00:23:26,330
Or a multimeter hooked to the output — it directly shows the potential on the lamp.

241
00:23:26,630 --> 00:23:28,750
Well, or a power source.

242
00:23:29,830 --> 00:23:38,570
For anyone who doesn't have one, you can take a well-charged battery and an ammeter.

243
00:23:38,650 --> 00:23:41,470
We're interested in the ammeter reading.

244
00:23:41,470 --> 00:23:52,550
The point of tuning is that we'll observe the voltage on the lamp and find the minimum consumption at which this voltage is maintained.

245
00:23:53,410 --> 00:24:00,410
Before the experiment, switch the trim pot slider to the minimum frequency mode.

246
00:24:00,570 --> 00:24:02,170
That's about 12 kHz.

247
00:24:03,310 --> 00:24:06,770
You'll hear the transformer working.

248
00:24:07,750 --> 00:24:09,590
So, apply power.

249
00:24:13,270 --> 00:24:14,770
Here's the consumption.

250
00:24:16,090 --> 00:24:20,770
2.86 A at 13.9 V.

251
00:24:20,930 --> 00:24:22,890
And the voltage on the lamp is 220 V.

252
00:24:23,070 --> 00:24:28,550
Now I'll move the lamp slightly to the side so it doesn't shine in the lens.

253
00:24:28,550 --> 00:24:40,870
The step-up transformer is slightly squeaking — and I start slowly rotating the trim pot.

254
00:24:43,390 --> 00:24:46,310
Observing current and voltage.

255
00:24:50,840 --> 00:24:56,640
The current, you see, starts falling, and the voltage stays.

256
00:24:59,840 --> 00:25:06,840
There's a point — 221 V, 2.8 A consumption.

257
00:25:09,640 --> 00:25:14,680
Further on, with frequency increase, consumption grows.

258
00:25:14,800 --> 00:25:23,920
Back off and find the minimum-consumption point.

259
00:25:23,920 --> 00:25:30,440
That's 2.8 A and voltage on the lamp 221 V.

260
00:25:31,720 --> 00:25:32,880
Next action.

261
00:25:33,200 --> 00:25:45,480
Unsolder the resistor, measure it, and pick a stationary working resistor to replace it that'll go on the board.

262
00:25:46,460 --> 00:25:50,920
This goes in place of the 10 kΩ.

263
00:25:52,240 --> 00:25:55,920
I unsoldered the resistor — here it is — now we measure it.

264
00:25:58,440 --> 00:26:06,600
So we see the resistance is 3.2 kΩ.

265
00:26:07,660 --> 00:26:13,200
And I found this resistor for myself — the closest to that value.

266
00:26:20,050 --> 00:26:24,670
Its resistance is 3.28 kΩ.

267
00:26:25,550 --> 00:26:26,930
Which suits well.

268
00:26:27,950 --> 00:26:32,330
You can also use these trim pots.

269
00:26:33,690 --> 00:26:37,430
You can buy them at 10 kΩ and install them on the board right away.

270
00:26:37,590 --> 00:26:41,210
It's multi-turn and you can set the operating point.

271
00:26:41,750 --> 00:26:50,670
But since this device will be used on the road, I decided to use this type of resistor.

272
00:26:51,380 --> 00:26:54,090
So I installed the resistor on the board.

273
00:26:55,130 --> 00:26:57,290
Now we can check consumption.

274
00:26:57,670 --> 00:26:59,130
Apply power.

275
00:27:00,110 --> 00:27:02,450
You see — 221 V.

276
00:27:03,510 --> 00:27:08,850
And consumption of 2.8 A.

277
00:27:09,170 --> 00:27:11,190
That fully suits us.

278
00:27:13,310 --> 00:27:16,730
So now, on to the tests.

279
00:27:16,730 --> 00:27:27,870
I think I'd planned to test this board operating in the 120-150 W range.

280
00:27:28,010 --> 00:27:35,730
Because my laptop charger consumes a maximum of 120 W.

281
00:27:37,590 --> 00:27:42,810
And so I'll always operate it in the up-to-50-W range.

282
00:27:42,810 --> 00:27:45,550
So let's arrange a check for it.

283
00:27:46,170 --> 00:27:47,850
At 200 W.

284
00:27:48,130 --> 00:27:52,570
I think such a small circuit will pull this.

285
00:27:53,990 --> 00:28:00,790
200 W will be consumption at 12 V power.

286
00:28:01,350 --> 00:28:03,110
Most likely about 15 A.

287
00:28:04,030 --> 00:28:06,470
This power supply won't pull it.

288
00:28:06,870 --> 00:28:12,170
So I'll bring out a car battery charger.

289
00:28:12,810 --> 00:28:16,350
Moving to a test on a 200 W lamp.

290
00:28:17,330 --> 00:28:21,590
While I was preparing and checking, a small accident happened.

291
00:28:22,830 --> 00:28:28,410
These EFR207 diodes in the diode bridge couldn't take it.

292
00:28:29,050 --> 00:28:34,430
At 150 W it worked great, but the 200 W lamp didn't withstand.

293
00:28:34,430 --> 00:28:47,270
Although at 230 V on a 200 W lamp the current through it is 0.87 A.

294
00:28:47,830 --> 00:28:53,470
And this current divided into 4 diodes — they should handle it normally.

295
00:28:53,610 --> 00:28:55,570
But one of them didn't survive.

296
00:28:56,230 --> 00:28:58,450
Moreover, it failed in an interesting way.

297
00:29:00,110 --> 00:29:02,030
The multimeter shows it's intact.

298
00:29:02,030 --> 00:29:09,930
And when you do a conductivity test at about 100 V, it starts breaking down.

299
00:29:10,390 --> 00:29:15,370
Either I got a defective one, or it actually couldn't withstand.

300
00:29:15,510 --> 00:29:19,470
But anyway, I replaced them with HER508 diodes.

301
00:29:19,830 --> 00:29:21,990
This will be reflected in the schematic too.

302
00:29:23,990 --> 00:29:24,850
Launch.

303
00:29:26,070 --> 00:29:27,770
200 W lamp.

304
00:29:28,990 --> 00:29:32,490
I recommend power supplies like this.

305
00:29:32,930 --> 00:29:34,670
That is, a charger.

306
00:29:34,970 --> 00:29:37,070
You can also use it as a power supply.

307
00:29:37,690 --> 00:29:41,470
It sets the battery charge current.

308
00:29:41,610 --> 00:29:43,890
But it works for our purposes too.

309
00:29:45,670 --> 00:29:46,190
Launch.

310
00:29:46,970 --> 00:29:51,630
You see 222 V on the lamp.

311
00:29:52,270 --> 00:29:55,410
Consumption slightly less than 15 A.

312
00:29:56,170 --> 00:30:01,530
There's some sag on the 200 W lamp.

313
00:30:03,070 --> 00:30:06,090
You can reduce by one turn.

314
00:30:06,170 --> 00:30:08,050
Then we'd get 230 V nominal.

315
00:30:08,150 --> 00:30:11,110
Or add a few more turns on the secondary.

316
00:30:11,650 --> 00:30:19,370
But I won't need to operate it at this power.

317
00:30:20,370 --> 00:30:30,050
So this is a test already with overload.

318
00:30:33,990 --> 00:30:42,790
On a trip or in field conditions, drawing 15 A from a battery will drain it fast.

319
00:30:42,790 --> 00:30:50,910
And besides — these days there are LED lamps.

320
00:30:51,210 --> 00:30:52,470
[Incandescents] make no sense.

321
00:30:52,830 --> 00:30:55,770
Because they release a lot of heat.

322
00:30:56,010 --> 00:30:56,690
Eat a lot.

323
00:30:57,470 --> 00:30:58,170
Light, yes.

324
00:31:00,870 --> 00:31:04,950
But the rest doesn't interest us.

325
00:31:05,130 --> 00:31:07,610
So it works better.

326
00:31:08,610 --> 00:31:13,510
Let me show what this system looks like on an LED lamp.

327
00:31:13,710 --> 00:31:15,750
It consumes only 11 W.

328
00:31:16,430 --> 00:31:22,330
And shines several times brighter than this 15 W lamp.

329
00:31:22,670 --> 00:31:25,790
Tens of times — there's no comparison at all.

330
00:31:26,410 --> 00:31:29,770
You see the circuit works on the lamp.

331
00:31:30,030 --> 00:31:31,010
The lamp's glowing.

332
00:31:32,550 --> 00:31:38,790
The charger power supply is maxed out at 15 A.

333
00:31:41,610 --> 00:31:43,850
What about the heat sink?

334
00:31:43,990 --> 00:31:47,330
The heat sink — I'd say about 60 degrees.

335
00:31:48,950 --> 00:31:51,470
Fingers start to burn.

336
00:31:52,750 --> 00:31:58,070
So yes, 200 W is heavy load for this converter.

337
00:31:58,150 --> 00:31:59,450
But nevertheless it works.

338
00:31:59,450 --> 00:32:02,490
And moreover, it works without forced cooling.

339
00:32:03,410 --> 00:32:08,250
So up to 150 W it's in an acceptable temperature range.

340
00:32:08,550 --> 00:32:10,710
Can work without a fan.

341
00:32:10,790 --> 00:32:17,850
And at 50 W or 80 W operation.

342
00:32:18,010 --> 00:32:21,130
It absolutely doesn't need additional airflow.

343
00:32:27,790 --> 00:32:29,490
Such a DIY thing.

344
00:32:29,490 --> 00:32:34,130
A lazy converter, basically.

345
00:32:35,830 --> 00:32:38,090
Whoever liked it — repeat it.

346
00:32:47,860 --> 00:32:48,700
Turn off.

347
00:32:50,840 --> 00:32:55,200
Now I'll show how the lamp works from this converter.

348
00:32:55,500 --> 00:32:56,400
LED.

349
00:32:57,480 --> 00:33:00,760
Its consumption is marked here.

350
00:33:01,280 --> 00:33:02,360
11 W.

351
00:33:03,960 --> 00:33:09,560
And compare its glow with a 15 W incandescent lamp.

352
00:33:10,940 --> 00:33:13,760
Apply power to the input.

353
00:33:15,720 --> 00:33:18,800
Look how this lamp shines.

354
00:33:19,860 --> 00:33:21,180
Just a flood of light.

355
00:33:21,980 --> 00:33:24,580
In field conditions this is plenty.

356
00:33:24,680 --> 00:33:26,740
And here's the consumption.

357
00:33:27,740 --> 00:33:31,760
We have 13.1 V.

358
00:33:31,860 --> 00:33:39,340
Multiply by 0.72 A.

359
00:33:40,940 --> 00:33:44,900
We get 9.5 W.

360
00:33:45,880 --> 00:33:59,320
Moreover, the chip itself has protection from supply voltage drop so the switches work in the optimal range.

361
00:34:00,100 --> 00:34:05,540
So if we lower the voltage — say the battery is discharging.

362
00:34:07,680 --> 00:34:11,780
10.6 V — the lamp is glowing.

363
00:34:15,380 --> 00:34:20,240
Threshold 8.4 V.

364
00:34:20,240 --> 00:34:22,440
The lamp is still glowing.

365
00:34:23,980 --> 00:34:26,580
But the battery never discharges to that level for us.

366
00:34:27,360 --> 00:34:28,480
That'd already be kaput.

367
00:34:28,740 --> 00:34:31,560
8.3 V.

368
00:34:32,920 --> 00:34:37,280
Startup happens around 9 V.

369
00:34:39,180 --> 00:34:47,520
And now compare with a test of a 15 W incandescent.

370
00:34:48,520 --> 00:34:49,560
Connect.

371
00:34:52,180 --> 00:34:57,660
And there's no comparison, naturally.

372
00:34:57,900 --> 00:35:05,640
So there's no point in field conditions to use these converters for incandescent lamps.

373
00:35:06,540 --> 00:35:09,180
Now two-lamp consumption.

374
00:35:11,460 --> 00:35:16,400
12.8 V.

375
00:35:16,400 --> 00:35:21,020
1.74 A.

376
00:35:23,980 --> 00:35:28,260
About 22.3 W.

377
00:35:31,580 --> 00:35:35,900
So I recommend using LED lamps.

378
00:35:37,720 --> 00:35:39,600
Next part of the video.

379
00:35:40,060 --> 00:35:41,480
A short continuation.

380
00:35:41,600 --> 00:35:45,940
Most likely it'll be uninteresting to those experienced in these matters.

381
00:35:46,760 --> 00:35:49,620
I'll give some advice to beginners.

382
00:35:50,260 --> 00:35:56,480
What tools are needed to make this lazy DIY.

383
00:35:58,880 --> 00:36:01,760
Now another moment — measure.

384
00:36:01,760 --> 00:36:06,520
How much does it draw without a load.

385
00:36:07,580 --> 00:36:09,240
Disconnect this lamp.

386
00:36:09,680 --> 00:36:12,120
Disconnect this.

387
00:36:15,380 --> 00:36:17,320
And look.

388
00:36:21,360 --> 00:36:23,360
Now multiply.

389
00:36:28,060 --> 00:36:32,700
12.8 times 0.07.

390
00:36:38,100 --> 00:36:39,880
What do we have?

391
00:36:41,340 --> 00:36:44,680
0.9 W at idle.

392
00:36:46,740 --> 00:36:51,240
Pretty good actually.

393
00:36:51,520 --> 00:36:55,500
For this kind of thing, without any stabilization.

394
00:36:56,960 --> 00:37:05,020
A minimum gentleman's tool kit for a beginner radio amateur.

395
00:37:06,100 --> 00:37:10,520
Who wants to replicate this converter.

396
00:37:12,240 --> 00:37:15,240
Accordingly, we need a screwdriver or drill.

397
00:37:16,760 --> 00:37:23,760
Because we need to drill holes for fastening bolts.

398
00:37:23,760 --> 00:37:28,940
Fastening the board itself and the transistors.

399
00:37:29,260 --> 00:37:34,080
And I attached the step-up transformer with a bolt.

400
00:37:35,560 --> 00:37:37,700
That's the first thing.

401
00:37:38,580 --> 00:37:40,540
What drills will we need?

402
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:48,920
We'll need a 3.2 mm drill.

403
00:37:48,920 --> 00:37:59,300
So that these bolts with 3 mm outer size pass through.

404
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:14,660
And we'll also need a 2.6 mm drill.

405
00:38:18,480 --> 00:38:22,580
You can buy 2.5 mm in stores.

406
00:38:24,280 --> 00:38:31,040
So we drilled a hole in the heat sink.

407
00:38:31,560 --> 00:38:39,700
And we could, with the tap — the M3 thread — cut a thread there.

408
00:38:40,200 --> 00:38:42,120
Tap the thread carefully.

409
00:38:42,120 --> 00:38:46,520
If it's aluminum, the metal is viscous, and you can easily break the tap.

410
00:38:46,720 --> 00:38:52,380
So I'd suggest greasing it with some lubricant when tapping.

411
00:38:52,840 --> 00:38:55,900
Simplest is to use WD-40.

412
00:38:59,380 --> 00:39:02,760
Two drills and the tap, don't forget.

413
00:39:02,760 --> 00:39:13,240
Add tweezers — very helpful for soldering small parts.

414
00:39:14,460 --> 00:39:20,620
Cutting tools — side cutters and small round-nose pliers.

415
00:39:22,580 --> 00:39:30,140
The wire I used for the 5.5-turn primary winding.

416
00:39:31,140 --> 00:39:45,300
Single-core, its core is 1.1 mm.

417
00:39:45,820 --> 00:39:53,540
And it's 1.8 mm with insulation outside.

418
00:39:53,540 --> 00:40:00,320
The wire I wound the step-up secondary with — this red one.

419
00:40:02,360 --> 00:40:04,540
Now let's measure it too.

420
00:40:07,760 --> 00:40:22,760
0.7 mm core and 1.4 mm with insulation.

421
00:40:27,980 --> 00:40:35,320
When wound on this core, here's how it's laid.

422
00:40:35,920 --> 00:40:42,880
First layer turn-to-turn, with no gaps around the full circumference.

423
00:40:42,980 --> 00:40:46,160
Then the second layer also from the inside, turn-to-turn.

424
00:40:46,280 --> 00:40:50,320
And the third layer is laid with this wire turn-to-turn.

425
00:40:50,320 --> 00:40:52,520
So it's wound in three layers.

426
00:40:52,600 --> 00:41:01,200
And that was enough on this core for us to get 220 V on the lamp under load.

427
00:41:03,060 --> 00:41:07,100
You adjust the voltage individually with the turn count.

428
00:41:07,360 --> 00:41:10,460
If the wire is slightly different — no problem.

429
00:41:11,320 --> 00:41:27,400
Besides buying the radio parts per the list of this schematic, don't forget to mandatorily get KPT thermal paste.

430
00:41:27,560 --> 00:41:31,520
Mine is KPT-19 non-drying thermal paste.

431
00:41:32,480 --> 00:41:40,200
And if you can find mica insulating pads for transistors — though they're rare now.

432
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:46,500
Most often you can find this material that has polyethylene on top.

433
00:41:47,520 --> 00:41:49,640
It protects from dust.

434
00:41:50,700 --> 00:41:57,860
This is a thermal-conductive material, while being insulating.

435
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:03,860
Because you can't mount transistors directly on the heat sink.

436
00:42:03,860 --> 00:42:14,480
Because this lead, where the bolt is fastened, is connected to the current.

437
00:42:14,820 --> 00:42:19,660
And if you fasten directly to metal, there will be a short circuit.

438
00:42:19,660 --> 00:42:22,080
So a gasket is mandatory.

439
00:42:22,640 --> 00:42:34,380
The gasket is placed at least 3 mm beyond this contact, the cooling surface.

440
00:42:35,820 --> 00:42:43,460
Smeared with thermal paste, and the transistor is installed on this substrate.

441
00:42:43,460 --> 00:42:49,120
And there's another small thing you might forget.

442
00:42:49,760 --> 00:42:56,680
These plastic insulator washers.

443
00:42:56,720 --> 00:43:06,380
They go on the screw that fastens the transistor to the heat sink.

444
00:43:07,380 --> 00:43:14,580
And when in place, the gasket sits in the transistor's eye.

445
00:43:15,860 --> 00:43:27,980
And prevents contact between the fastening bolt and the metal lead of the transistor.

446
00:43:28,980 --> 00:43:37,000
Also a critical thing, because if you just screw it in, there'll be a short circuit.

447
00:43:38,780 --> 00:43:40,800
And basically that's all.

448
00:43:41,240 --> 00:43:44,980
Soldering iron and solder.

449
00:43:46,500 --> 00:43:57,440
If you have no experience, you might need about a day with breaks to make this thing.

450
00:43:57,440 --> 00:44:01,340
For me it took one day.

451
00:44:02,820 --> 00:44:09,400
Literally 5-6 hours to wind, assemble, and tune.

452
00:44:10,340 --> 00:44:12,360
Now about the mounting.

453
00:44:13,700 --> 00:44:18,240
There are a few rules useful for beginners.

454
00:44:19,380 --> 00:44:23,180
This is power electronics mounting.

455
00:44:24,180 --> 00:44:31,860
The leads going from the chip through the resistor to the transistors should be the shortest possible length.

456
00:44:32,120 --> 00:44:36,740
In general everything that controls the transistors should be as short as possible.

457
00:44:36,880 --> 00:44:42,660
That is, the chip is located closest to the power switches.

458
00:44:44,480 --> 00:44:53,700
This way you reduce pickups, parasitic ringing, and other negative phenomena that may show up during converter operation.

459
00:44:55,360 --> 00:44:58,660
I already explained why this cap is needed.

460
00:44:59,880 --> 00:45:01,520
Mandatorily put it in.

461
00:45:02,060 --> 00:45:05,080
This is a ceramic capacitor.

462
00:45:06,660 --> 00:45:12,560
Ceramic capacitors at 50 V — like these, yellow color.

463
00:45:12,920 --> 00:45:17,940
And work with mounting density as tight as possible.

464
00:45:17,940 --> 00:45:21,220
So we don't have big distances between parts.

465
00:45:21,680 --> 00:45:25,280
They're practically all next to each other.

466
00:45:28,300 --> 00:45:31,440
The diode bridge — doesn't matter how you make it.

467
00:45:32,540 --> 00:45:33,860
Reservoir cap.

468
00:45:34,060 --> 00:45:36,720
And don't forget to put this resistor in.

469
00:45:38,300 --> 00:45:46,940
Because residual charge on the capacitors — if it doesn't discharge — you can get hit, and it'll be very unpleasant.

470
00:45:48,680 --> 00:45:53,460
After this thing the voltage can be high, and here's residual.

471
00:45:54,820 --> 00:45:58,840
Don't pay attention to these leads, those are my taps further on.

472
00:45:59,580 --> 00:46:03,440
Here 70 V and here 135 V.

473
00:46:03,740 --> 00:46:06,040
Relative to the start of the wire.

474
00:46:07,380 --> 00:46:18,560
And if operating up to 50 W, you can fully put it in some box, even without leaving cooling holes.

475
00:46:19,300 --> 00:46:25,920
If more than 50 W, you can position the heat sink so it sticks out of the box for cooling.

476
00:46:27,060 --> 00:46:34,420
The heat sink dimensions are 6 cm in length.

477
00:46:37,820 --> 00:46:42,020
Width practically 3.5 cm.

478
00:46:42,900 --> 00:46:51,900
And this dimension is 1.7 cm.

479
00:46:52,560 --> 00:47:03,880
When you pick a heat sink, this part should be as thick as possible relative to these cooling ribs.

480
00:47:04,660 --> 00:47:07,560
And basically that's all — nothing tricky here.

481
00:47:07,700 --> 00:47:10,780
You can tune it all without instruments.

482
00:47:11,740 --> 00:47:15,820
I already showed how to do that, and this thing starts up right away.

483
00:47:17,260 --> 00:47:22,320
A small downside is that this circuit is open-loop.

484
00:47:22,320 --> 00:47:28,620
If you leave it without load, high potential can build up here.

485
00:47:29,300 --> 00:47:33,900
Significantly above 350 V.

486
00:47:35,200 --> 00:47:38,820
I took a 450 V capacitor — that's enough.

487
00:47:40,780 --> 00:47:45,020
But I'll tinker with this circuit a bit more.

488
00:47:46,260 --> 00:47:49,080
I'll lay out this circuit, then show how it works.

489
00:47:50,040 --> 00:47:53,840
This chip has one wonderful property.

490
00:47:53,980 --> 00:48:03,840
If you apply logical zero to pin 3 — simply apply minus of the power source — it stops generation.

491
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:10,120
I think on this principle you can make voltage feedback.

492
00:48:10,120 --> 00:48:17,360
For example, to hold 330 V DC at the output.

493
00:48:17,780 --> 00:48:23,340
The cap reaches 330 V and the chip stops generation.

